			<p>Professor Fish,</p>
<p>I&#8217;d like to thank you for three wonderful essays on teaching writing. I am a math professor, and I believe that the challenges of teaching mathematics parallel closely those of teaching writing. Much of what you wrote parallel my views on how students should learn how to do mathematics.</p>
<p>Just as there is much confusion between the subject of English literature and the skill or craft of writing English, there is a similar confusion between the field of mathematics and the skill or craft of doing mathematics. Too many people seem to believe that if you teach students about a subject, then the students will somehow learn the underlying skills.</p>
<p>What I also like is your willingness to explicitly confront students with the abstract structure of grammar and writing. Too many teachers today shy away from this and hope that students will somehow acquire the proper understanding of grammar and corresponding writing skills unconsciously by osmosis. The same is true in mathematics education, where we refuse to teach deductive logic explicitly to students and hope vainly that students will figure it out implicitly.</p>

		</div>
