	<div class="the-comment" id="comment-94065">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">MC</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-94065" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">September 7, 2009</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">11:38 pm</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>Dear Professor Fish,</p>
<p>  I&#8217;d like to moderate my comments from Part 1 that you cited in Part 2 (I believe you felt I was questioning your authority in composition&#8211; that is to say, you were unhappy with my assertion that &#8220;you don&#8217;t know a damn thing about teaching writing&#8221;).  For the record, my primary critique was of the pedagogy I thought you were advocating, though at that point your approach wasn&#8217;t at all clear.  Now that it&#8217;s somewhat clearer, let me congratulate you on having a tremendous amount right.  As a former teacher in the rural black public schools of the Mississippi Delta, and as veteran comp. instructor of low-income, at-risk students of color and immigrants, I commend your stand against a &#8216;soft multiculturalism&#8217; that refuses to offer students the power inherent in the language of&#8211; power.  </p>
<p> Yet I also believe that this pedagogical approach you advocate&#8211; teaching grammar without the jargon, teaching the sentence as a logical form, teaching the importance of syntax and grammar in creating meaning, would be woefully incomplete even if your sole objective was to teach the proper sentence.  Yes, sentences lead to paragraphs, and so on and so on, only&#8230; well, that&#8217;s not how human beings communicate.  That&#8217;s perhaps how Milton has Satan communicate; that&#8217;s how an intellectual of Stanley Fish&#8217;s ability is able to understand written communication that has risen to the level of poetry.  But we&#8217;re not talking about teaching students to write timeless prose&#8230; we&#8217;re talking about teaching students rhetoric and argumentation  in blocks of 3-7 pages, ie, the college-level essay.  </p>
<p>  I do believe there&#8217;s a place for much of the pedagogy you describe, and your focus on the sentence would work well to help students focus on the sentence as a necessary unit of meaning.  Yet the objective(s) of a composition class are   myriad.  Perhaps students ought to spend more time on a reasonable, practical, and exploratory approach to grammar that helps them comprehend the logical integrity of the sentence.  Yet composition programs are charged with teaching sustained argument&#8211; specific, analyzed examples must create an unified, focused, significant argument.  Students have opinions, but not reasons; they have experience and convictions, but lack the apparatus to express a position.  That is why good composition pedagogy attempts to do what you suggest&#8211; teach grammar and syntax, ie, the necessity of form in making meaning&#8211; while simultaneously trying to engage students in areas of their own experience to begin to create arguments.  I don&#8217;t think  that nine weeks of inventing one&#8217;s own language/grammar (the idea being that you&#8217;d learn those structures well through tedious exploration?), and a tenth week of &#8220;They Say, I Say,&#8221; is an adequate pedagogy for teaching argument to students who don&#8217;t know anything about written argument.  And your quick skirt around the connection between careful reading and careful writing is ridiculous given the research we have about the ways students learn grammar&#8230; I bet you wrote good sentences without a Catholic school teacher, or a Stanley Fish, simply because you were a prolific reader.  </p>
<p>  There&#8217;s a reason that composition studies exist.  Have your read Mike Rose, for example?  These are complicated issues.  It&#8217;s not that silliness and idiocy and mediocrity doesn&#8217;t exist in Composition, or that the Academy more generally doesn&#8217;t consider and even nurture a lot of absurd and counterproductive foolishness.  But you&#8217;re still mostly wrong on this one.  </p>
<p>  Michael Copperman<br />
  University of Oregon</p>

