	<div class="the-comment alt" id="comment-94071">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">Thomas Zaslavsky</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-94071" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">September 7, 2009</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">11:59 pm</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>I agree with this column.  I am very sympathetic to the existence of many dialects and many languages.  At the same time I&#8217;m very sympathetic to the idea of a common language within which large numbers of people can communicate accurately and precisely.  Confining the discussion to English, the former are, for example, all the interesting dialects of English from many villages and social classes.  The latter is standard English.  For communicating effectively with one&#8217;s subgroup, their dialect is likely to be most effective.  For communicating with people of all kinds of backgrounds, as in scholarship and national or global, or even statewide, business, one has to know and use standard English.  </p>
<p>I teach mathematics; I cannot understand a math solution written in (for example) street talk, and neither can anyone else, because the precision necessary to logical expression doesn&#8217;t exist in such dialects.  They have other virtues, but not that.</p>
<p>Creative writing and creative use of language is wonderful, but if you cannot communicate accurately when necessary, you are handicapped.</p>

		</div>
	</div><!-- #comment-## -->
	<div class="the-comment" id="comment-94073">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">Hari C</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-94073" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">September 8, 2009</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">12:04 am</span>
