		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>I usually agree with Stanley Fish, but this part 3 seems the weakest of the three arguments.  The first two were much better articles with more of a stable foundation outlining some reasonable objections on his part.</p>
<p>Just because&#8211;the cccc recognizes that students have a right to their own language and dialect&#8211; does not mean&#8211; that comp instructors are subverting standards or forms to the detriment of student success.  Comp instructors do try to improve their student&#8217;s standard English; that is the job.  Just because their professional organization recognizes a right of the student does not mean that comp instruction should be assumed to be fatally compromised as Stanley Fish does.</p>
<p>Sure teaching at the sentence level is important, And, of course, if you abandon all formalities about writing then you are not preparing the students for the next class, or the writing that awaits them beyond that.  </p>
<p>But, how do you do it?  Teach &#8220;forms&#8221;? Stanley Fish&#8217;s way more work for him, but its highly unlikely to work effectively for  others because it treats grammar outside of the context of the student&#8217;s writing.  By the way, isn&#8217;t it ironic that you goad the cccc for recognizing student rights of expression as somehow dangerous, but you waste student time by having them make up and present a fake language.  Wouldn&#8217;t they be better off doing presentations on how they revised a paper to correct or improve it at the sentence level?</p>
<p>Teaching and requiring students to revise their own work to correct and optimize grammar with lots of individual instruction as needed is important.  Teach in whole class, small groups&#8211;and have individual tutorial assistance available for the real project of revising at least one or two major papers of the course.  </p>
<p>Use exercises that resemble ones from papers they have written.  Teaching not only correcting grammar but combining and structuring sentences to express ideas more effectively.  Not just the names of sentence parts but the rhetorical options and manueverings that grammar allows.</p>
<p>These kinds of teaching moves and others that make the grammar less abstract and more a part of their actual writing situation is actually the new school and better way of teaching &#8220;forms&#8221; and helping people improve at the sentence level.  </p>
<p>Stanley&#8217;s Fish&#8217;s way sounds pretty much like rote grammar drills that have not been explained in terms of how Fish&#8217;s students apply the knowledge to their actual writing.  Researchers have empirically proven that grammar boot camp does not really work, but Stanley Fish wants us to ignore that and accept it on faith that grammar can save the student and the university if it was just taught.  Teaching grammar effectively is not as simple as Mr. Fish breaks it down to be.   </p>
<p>Learning grammar in the context of a student&#8217;s own writing is not just a silly mantra but a really practical tool that works because the student is engaged with their own writing and not jumping through formalistic hoops, not matter how pre-eminent the person who designed the hoops is.</p>

		</div>
	</div><!-- #comment-## -->
	<div class="the-comment alt" id="comment-94077">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">Russell Potter, Ph.D.</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-94077" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">September 8, 2009</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">12:10 am</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>Professor Fish offers this as the pith of his stalk of wisdom: &#8220;You don’t strike a blow against a power structure by making yourself vulnerable to its prejudices. &#8221;  Perhaps not.  But you certainly don&#8217;y strike any sort of blow by avoiding offense to those same prejudices.  This is a well-known fallacy, which has been exploded with particular verve by Rosina Lippi-Green, who refers to this as the &#8220;language subordination model.&#8221;  Teachers, acting on the false premise that they are, by insisting that students cowtow to a variety of groundless rhetorical prejudices (disguised as &#8220;rules&#8221;), take a vanguard role: &#8220;I am stopping you from writing/speaking this way because others will be prejudiced against you if you carry on with such usage.&#8221;  And yet, ironically, this insistance reinscribes the very &#8220;rules&#8221; that the teachers claim have external existance.</p>
<p>Fish&#8217;a playful assignments &#8212; and I too love Austin, Truss, and Kolln &#8212; bely his underlying message, which is that some ostensible &#8220;choices&#8221; may well be judged &#8212; and harshly &#8212; and that we should accede to such judgments as a condition of &#8220;education.&#8221;  Let&#8217;s make no mistake that language and power are related &#8212; but let&#8217;s also be clear that the demands of power far exceed any rational correspondence between form and function.</p>

		</div>
	</div><!-- #comment-## -->
	<div class="the-comment" id="comment-94079">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">C.C.</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-94079" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">September 8, 2009</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">12:12 am</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>Yes, trying to wrestle logical thoughts into sentences is very important, and your formal approach sounds effective. But it&#8217;s just as important to help students understand what an idea is if we hope to help them clarify their own thoughts in writing  and to understand the thoughts of others. Otherwise they will be confined to the rather flat world of statements and counter-statements. In expository prose most sentences &#8212; except for those written by Hegel, perhaps &#8212; are elements of larger ideas. They&#8217;re statements cruising around looking for other statements they can connect with in order to form a larger assertion or idea. For the most part, paragraphs are the smallest units able to express at least the outlines of an idea. A formal approach to paragraph building is still one of the best ways of allowing students to experience the thrill of fleshing out a cogent idea that can be debated with others objectively, without any fear of being personally criticized. </p>
<p>Mr. Fish, in the future I hope you will discuss the love-hate relationship between sentences and paragraphs. Paragraphing is just as essential to writing as &#8220;sentencing&#8221; is. I hope you will share with us some of your suggestions for helping students to paragraph better.</p>

		</div>
	</div><!-- #comment-## -->
	<div class="the-comment alt" id="comment-94081">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">Mark Hammond</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-94081" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">September 8, 2009</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">12:25 am</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>Resorting to numbering main points? Seems as if Mr. Fish has a problem organizing, which is a basic writing skill. </p>
<p>The Elements of Style is filled with lots of good things, not just sentence structure. The forward of the book alone is far more inspiring that Mr. Fish. </p>
<p>Strunk would cringe at the word choice &#8220;facile egalitarianism of soft multiculturalism&#8221; being used in the New York Times.</p>
<p>I give this a C-</p>

		</div>
	</div><!-- #comment-## -->
	<div class="the-comment" id="comment-94083">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">MCM</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-94083" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">September 8, 2009</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">12:28 am</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>You are absolutely right in your conclusion. The ability to analyze sentences and arguments is crucial in being able to write well. Good writing is mainly about structure and organization and secondly about verbal fluency and vocabulary. Even if one lacks fluency or a good &#8220;ear,&#8221; matters of style can easily be fixed in the editing process.</p>
<p>I would disagree with anyone who would claim that an abundance of reading makes a good writer. It certainly doesn&#8217;t hurt, but I&#8217;ve known plenty of well-read folks who have no idea how to place a comma.</p>

		</div>
	</div><!-- #comment-## -->
	<div class="the-comment alt" id="comment-94085">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">Tom</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-94085" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">September 8, 2009</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">12:29 am</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>Amen to all that.  I&#8217;ve been teaching writing courses since 1965, most recently [for the past decade plus] in law school.  Oddly enough, I find that most of my students in law school are not capable of analyzing what they have written.  They can parse a statute or a rule of court, to figure out what to do with it; but they can&#8217;t parse a simple sentence.  And therefore, they have trouble writing clearly.  Though it should have happened before they reached that plateau of education, I spend a good bit of time discussing sentence structures and the logic of composition.  They generally catch on after a while.  But it&#8217;s something that they should have been exposed to much earlier.  It would have made them better lawyers.</p>

		</div>
	</div><!-- #comment-## -->
	<div class="the-comment" id="comment-94087">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">jay fraser</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-94087" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">September 8, 2009</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">12:38 am</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>That&#8217;s a grand approach to writing and one I have used time and again.  But it requires the teacher to learn the rhetoric and logic that lie behind that approach.  Most places try to &#8220;control&#8221; the composition courses by requiring textbooks, usually collections of essays, with the implicit pressure to teach reading and argument.  One practically sneaks in the rhetoric/grammar approach.  Or, one is imprisoned in a department dominated by &#8220;creative writing&#8221; where the mission is allowing students to &#8220;be creative&#8221; by the usual navel gazing for the young.  Adjuncts (who teach most of the composition classes in the U.S.) simply don&#8217;t have the control to choose your texts, and most have little training in language and rhetoric which are now rarely required in graduate school curricula.  So who will teach the teachers?</p>

		</div>
	</div><!-- #comment-## -->
	<div class="the-comment alt" id="comment-94089">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">Allie</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-94089" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">September 8, 2009</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">12:43 am</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>You also need small writing seminars (no more than 12 students; 9 is perfect) plus an instructor prepared to do heavy, heavy editing on every piece of student prose during the first half of the term. You walk them through close readings. You coach them into detailed, considerate in-class critique.  And you have them read aloud, a lot&#8211;the ear often tells them more than the eye. You encourage, chide, challenge, reassure. And then, cunningly, you shift the burden. Peer edits, &#8216;cut-this-by-25%-good-now-cut-by-50%-and-now-by-75%&#8217; exercises&#8230;and by the tenth week you can simply put a  &#8216;x&#8217; in the margin of any piece of their prose and they&#8217;ll know what to do, or at least make a plausible  guess. But oh, the labor, if the instructor is both literate and conscientious. And oh, the pathetic paycheck.</p>

		</div>
	</div><!-- #comment-## -->
	<div class="the-comment" id="comment-94091">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">Tony Waters</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-94091" title="Comment Permalink">
