		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>Good job, Mr. Fish&#8211;a few observations:</p>
<p>1) Like you, I am not convinced that the key to quality writing is quantity reading.  Is there evidence that reading a lot makes people better writers, and is there evidence that reading, let’s say, graphic novels daily has made of those readers better writers? Or is it just possible that the same people who like to write like to read (tangent: remember “Classics Illustrated?).</p>
<p>2) Experienced teachers today know that reading is not a popular activity among most students. Getting them to read “The Wolverine” or “Gossip Girls” is not the problem. Getting them to debate is even less feasible. They’re working on their social networking skills.</p>
<p>3) As to those who wrote that“&#8230;we are teaching in cooperation with a discriminatory power system,”&#8211;well, yes. That’s the point. And if you want to get into the power system, you’d better know how to do what it wants you to do. Just as you say.</p>
<p>The sentence=based approach you use is a good one. It would be even better if students were exposed to such a method at a much younger age, so a college teacher could deal with even more matters related to good writing&#8211;paragraphs, say.</p>

		</div>
