	<div class="the-comment alt" id="comment-94107">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">Stephen</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-94107" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">September 8, 2009</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">1:04 am</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>While Professor Fish continues to make excellent progress in laying out what he proposes writing classes should look like, he also continues NOT to engage seriously with content-based alternatives.  The examples he points to, such as the CCC, are not hard to disagree with.  But he refuses once again to engage at all with the vast middle ground between teaching content without forms and teaching forms without content.</p>
<p>If I were advising a student who had a choice between Professor Fish&#8217;s sentence-based course and a course that would teach them about logical arguments, use of evidence, organization, paraphrasing/summarizing, and coherence (as well as dramatically less time on sentence-level editing), I would advise almost every student I&#8217;ve ever taught to take the latter.  The sentence is simply not my highest priority.  Yes, everything else is built out of sentences, but they can be built out of mediocre sentences at need.  I&#8217;d rather have students who know how to manage content, and are weak with sentences, than students who are great with sentences, but haven&#8217;t been exposed to how to write an essay (or business memo, or any other sort of report).</p>
<p>Professor Fish, I encourage you to write a 4th episode in this enthralling series, in which you engage the claim that there are OTHER SKILLS that firstyear composition courses can legitimately be expected to cover, and explain why you&#8217;re willing to throw all of them overboard to fixate entirely on content-less sentences.</p>

		</div>
